  "text": "To further divide the inferior parietal lobe and delineate SMG and AG, we used established cortical landmarks as regional boundaries. The origin of the PISJ marks the superior division between the SMG and AG and was used as the posterior boundary of SMG (see Introduction and SMG protocol in the supplementary S2 File). The PISJ is similarly considered a boundary indicator by other authors [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The subdivision results in the two horseshoe-shaped regions of the SMG and AG enclosing the SF and AS respectively. Although the PISJ was not prominent in many brains, it was at least vaguely discernible or seen clearly forming a dimple in all but one hemisphere.",
